[Borrowing from a prior ProMED-mail posting moderator comment (Botulism,
wound, drug-related - UK: alert 20020223.3614), wound botulism has been
reported in injecting drug users (IDUs) in the United States and in
Europe. Association with drug injection was first reported in 1982 in New
York City (1). In 1995 there were 19 cases reported in California
associated with contaminated black tar heroin (2). In 1998 there was an
outbreak of 5 cases reported in Switzerland, all associated with illicit
injection drug use.
In October 2001 ProMED reported a case of wound botulism in Scotland, and
questioned whether the heightened surveillance for unusual illness in IDUs,
as an aftermath of the outbreak of _C. novyi_ associated with contaminated
heroin might have led to isolated case reports. In this article there is
mention of 13 cases since the beginning of the year, suggesting the
possibility of a contaminated batch of heroin on the market in the UK,
somewhat reminiscent of the outbreak in California in 1995 (2). One wonders
if other countries have been seeing a similar increase in wound botulism in
recent months.
1. CDC. Wound Botulism Associated with Parenteral Cocaine Abuse -- New
York City. MMWR. 26 Feb 1982 /
31(7);87-8 <http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00000208.htm>
2. CDC. Wound Botulism -- California, 1995. MMWR. 8 Dec 1995 /
44(48);889-892 <http://www.cdc.gov/epo/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00039732.htm>
- Mod. MPP]
